##DC Journal | Stock Up Guide for incomplete epidemics

Micro signal

Features are presented, some fairly limited thoughts and memories.

Well, what's done is done. The school will be closed, the exams will be renewed, and online classes will be started. Yesterday Amis asked me what I would like to stock up on, so thanks to cornstreet chef, I'd like to share a few tips. (for domestic friends, there is no need to refer to it. I'm sure you're already skilled at it, and I'm proud of the price and convenience of life.)
And said, "in the first place,
Before talking about what to buy, I think the first thing you need to know is your own storage environment, such as how big the refrigerator is, how it's cooled, where you're going to put things in addition to the refrigerator, and whether the heat is still on in your house? And then we'll figure out the best way to stock up. If you buy too much, you'll either run out of room or break.

And then we have to figure out how long to stock up. It's called stocking up, but you're going back to the supermarket anyway, just to cut back on the crowds. Based on my own shopping experience and eating habits, a well-stocked grocery store can last for about two and a half weeks. Vegetables are hard to resist. And the marginal benefit of stocking up, especially on food, is greatly diminished. Therefore, the following recommendations are also based on this time span, I hope you rationally stock up, science stock up.

Food Selection & Storage
Generally speaking, staple food and meat are easy to put, vegetables are not easy to put. Staple food raw room temperature preservation is good, meat frozen, vegetable roots and stems good place, green leafy vegetables have some difficulties.

The choice of vegetables I think there are a few key points: long storage loss rate is low, not easy to frostbite, not easy to cover bad.

- Low wastage rate: some vegetables can be eaten after a long time, but they taste much worse, or there are more inedible parts (such as yellowed and rotten leaves) .
- LESS FROSTBITE: I think it's better to keep the fridge cold if you're stocking up, but it's also easy to freeze some fragile vegetables.
- Not easily spoiled: Vegetables are either dry or wet. If you don't want it to get wet, leave it open. But in the case of stock, open one to save space (can not stack) , second, I think the refrigerator is too much to keep open hygiene, third, you have to worry about whether at home will grow mushrooms, what's with the mushrooms and everything.

Some people think that vegetables should be kept clean, but I think it's better not to wash them, cut them, remove the vines, or choose the leaves. That way, what's left of it will only be what you don't want.
PSST. Don't buy frozen vegetables don't buy frozen vegetables don't buy frozen vegetables. It's not like we don't have fresh vegetables. The frozen ones are not cost-effective and don't taste good. The cooked ones are all watery. I don't think it's necessary.

Some of the vegetables I find easy to put and cheap are:
- RHIZOMES: carrot, White Radish, sweet potato, Taro
This should be the best variety to stock, and can be kept for a long time in cold storage. Sweet potatoes are fine at room temperature. Some would say potatoes, but I'm not a potato hoarder. If you want to store it, please cook it and put it in the freezer, otherwise I will show you every minute.
- Squash and tomato: squash, tomato, Zucchini
Squash can be stored at room temperature Safeway recently had $4 for $5, and tomatoes can be refrigerated for up to two weeks.
- Flower Buds: Broccoli, cauliflower
Still recommend cooked send frozen, otherwise the refrigeration method is a bit complex and take up space.
- leafy vegetables: CABBAGE, Chinese cabbage (leafy Greens are cheap and can be pushed) , onion, celery
The hardest category to keep, if you really want to buy a big, cheap bowl of super green leafy vegetables, is as follows:
Step 1: Wet Your kitchen paper
Step 2: Gently wrap the root of the vegetable
Step 3: put it in a Ziplock bag
Step 4: Vertically into the refrigerator tupperware
Step 5: Remember to check the kitchen paper every now and then to see if it's dry and the leaves are turning yellow
- Special Separate: Remember to buy scallions, Ginger, garlic! It's old, but it's easy to miss. Trust me, you don't want to go out on a special trip because you don't have any onions, ginger, or garlic in your home, but some dishes have no relish and are soulless. Also, Ginger needs to buy dry, whole. (I thought this was common sense, but after seeing someone buy a bag of very wet, cut ginger, I thought it worth mentioning...)

Meat is easy. It's fair to say that you can store any meat you want, but remember to cut it up / divide it up / freeze it mindlessly as long as it's not part of your diet for the next two days.
- Wannian County recommends frozen shrimp. PUT IT Away.-you're worth it. Coastal communities say they can't live without seafood (Safeway recently offered two-for-one and Harris Teeter often has frozen shrimp specials) 
But if you buy loose-weight seafood and bring it back frozen (the package is not very sealed that kind of) , remember to separate from other food, some cold-resistant bacteria is not frozen to death.
- seasoned meat is good, too. Hormel has a flavored tenderloin. It's cheap, it's delicious, it's convenient. But look at the expiration date on the cured meat.
- shredded meat / minced meat cooked and refrigerated is much more reliable than raw meat. If you don't want to burn it right away, it's recommended to buy a fancy-looking package with a four-ring seal (left-hand side of the image below) , and one with its own Styrofoam (right-hand side) that loses color in minutes.
- Defrost meat, refrigerate, remove to room temperature and allow to thaw. It's supposed to be antibacterial. Remember not to freeze it repeatedly.
I don't have to tell you about grain, but rice and flour are kept at room temperature, and bread is frozen.
As for fast-food snacks, this is not in my line of business (I found out that the CSL does not have instant noodles from Southeast Asia, nor does it use good Japanese instant noodles, which is too bad) . I'm sure all my brothers and sisters are better at it than I am

Tell me about the fridge
- temperature
Just said the refrigerator temperature to turn down a little thing, the basic model of my apartment refrigerator refrigeration can gross estimate the temperature, I believe we can also. You don't have to fill it up, just chill it a little.
- space
First of all, I don't think anyone has a freezer in their house, so think about how you can use your freezer space.
Generally speaking, the air-conditioner sinks, and it is colder in the air than in the air. The arrangement can be seen in this guide to penguins. (but I advise you to give up the bean products, unless you go to the Chinese Super League to buy something frozen bean curd, otherwise it is quite a struggle. And Dry goods... just keep it at room temperature, but here also can not buy dry goods, unless go to the Chinese Super League.)
- keep clean and confirm shelf life
When you're at home, check out the kids in your fridge to make sure they're healthy, so you'll be healthy.

Tell me about the life around us
Thanks to the blessing of fairy fellow, with a mask emergency can go shopping. I think there's still plenty of stock in the Chinese Super Market, but the local supermarket, at a glance, can see the rhythm of people stocking up in the United States.

There was plenty of fruit and vegetables, but meat and milk... I had never seen such empty shelves at Safeway.
There's a lot of water in the VATS, but the disappearance of small bottles of water.
CVS needless to say, hygiene products, disinfectants, and rolls of paper that everyone cares about are all items to stock up on. (btw, I think people should get some hand cream. Hand sanitizer hurts.)

While my community is not yet panic-buy, I hear there are large shortages in some densely populated areas, particularly of water and paper. Each big supermarket also sends the notice in succession, urges everybody to store goods rationally.
I've always wondered why suppliers / Govt don't anticipate "just-in-time" needs, like medical supplies, hygiene supplies, and necessities? I don't see the wisdom in treating people. But kids can choose Besiege Wèi to rescue Zhào and shop farther afield, so don't skimp on cab fare during an outbreak.

From the DMV's first confirmed case, to the DMV's full-line failure, to the growing cases, to the cancel in-person classes, to D. C. Declare State of emergency, then shut down all the way to public schools, not to mention those two epic meltdowns, it's been a surprisingly fast week. The apathetic majority of the American public is finally waking up to one alarm after another. It's a little crass, but I really think this is your country's own recipe for magical reality.

When I retweeted the question of whether wearing a mask would be discriminatory, my American friend told the truth:
Last week I had a chance to have a simple conversation with the American public health people. I asked why you don't wear masks, "One, we're told the virus isn't that serious, and two, You are protecting others, but You can not protect yourself. " My WTF is literally on the tip of my tongue. Is it bad for others to Protect others? But DC citizens are friends. Kiss test wearing a mask walking on the road, just be passers-by looked at a few more, keep a distance detour, I think this is also quite good. And I saw a foreigner in a mask in the supermarket, and suddenly I thought, even he was not white, that's a good sign.

At this point, we suddenly received a call from the national emergency. I think of a Game Theory teacher who just saw a friend retweeting a comment to the effect that it is now the biggest challenge for the self centered people of Europe and the US, and that only cooperation can reap the greatest benefits. There are a few hotels in my neighborhood, and the spring tour groups have a Poepoe every day. It is said that every spring, people come to DC to see the Cherry Blossoms in People Mountain People Sea, just like Gu Cun Park. It is sometimes thought that it is not human action that determines what is natural, but natural action that determines what is human. Well, we're all grown-ups now, and we need to take responsibility for our actions. At the same time, the news coming online is also a kind of magical reality, and I don't think now is the time to talk about conspiracy, but rather to look at the scientistmedics, to look at the level of governance, to look at whether we can collaborate to pay off.

Anyway, ordinary people do what they can. Make adequate preparations, reduce in-person contact and unnecessary touch, wash hands frequently, disinfect the door handle from time to time, go to a crowded place and come back to wash your clothes and wash your hair... although the rate of infection in healthy young people is not high, but everything has to be considered in case, think of all the trouble that comes next, think of the medical costs of the United States, think of the people around you who are likely to be affected... forget it, it's not worth it. To protect oneself is to protect others, and to protect others is to protect oneself.

The outbreak is continuing, but it will pass. Whether we miss this year's Cherry blossoms or not, we'll meet again. Finally, to quote the lovely Francys: "Let's look out for one another.happy webinars. ".
